Bike Sharing Demand

Mohit Rajput

Introduction

Bike sharing systems are a means of renting bicycles where the process of obtaining membership, rental, and bike return is automated via a network of kiosk locations throughout a city. Using these systems, people are able rent a bike from a one location and return it to a different place on an as-needed basis. Currently, there are over 500 bike-sharing programs around the world.
The data generated by these systems makes them attractive for researchers because the duration of travel, departure location, arrival location, and time elapsed is explicitly recorded. Bike sharing systems therefore function as a sensor network, which can be used for studying mobility in a city.

Research Question

To combine historical usage patterns with weather data in order to forecast bike rental demand in the Capital Bikeshare program.

Discussion

The Dataset contains p=12 i.e 12 variables and n=10886 i.e. 10886 observations. the variable types are as shown below-

Categorical Numerical
datetime atemp
season temp
holiday humidity
workingday windspeed
weather casual
registered
count

Data Cookbook

Data Field
datetime hourly date + timestamp
season 1 = spring, 2 = summer, 3 = fall, 4 = winter
holiday whether the day is considered a holiday
workingday whether the day is neither a weekend nor holiday
weather 1: Clear, Few clouds, Partly cloudy, Partly cloudy
2: Mist + Cloudy, Mist + Broken clouds, Mist + Few clouds, Mist
3: Light Snow, Light Rain + Thunderstorm + Scattered clouds, Light Rain + Scattered clouds
4: Heavy Rain + Ice Pallets + Thunderstorm + Mist, Snow + Fog
temp temperature in Celsius
atemp “feels like” temperature in Celsius
humidity relative humidity
Windspeed wind speed
casual number of non-registered user rentals initiated
registered number of registered user rentals initiated
count numberof total rentals

Corelation matrix

Checking the correlation between dependent variable, also checking if the sum of casual and registered is truely equal to count.

sub1<-data.frame(training$count, (training$registered + training$casual), training$registered, training$casual)
corrplot(cor(sub1), method="shade", shade.col=NA, cl.pos="n", tl.col="black", tl.srt=30, addCoef.col="black")

On observing the above plot it becomes clear that indeed count is a proper sum of casual and registered.

Now checkind the relation between dependent and independent variable.

sub2<-data.frame(training$count, training$registered, training$casual, training$temp, training$humidity, training$atemp,training$windspeed, tim$year, tim$mon, tim$hour, tim$mday)

modfit1_2 <- rpart(casual ~ year + month + hour + season + holiday + workingday + weather + temp + humidity + windspeed, data = trainSet)

3.Creating model using tree with complete training set

# atemp is highly corelated to temp, no much variation between day,
set.seed(22349)
modfit3_1 <- rpart(registered ~ year + month + hour + season + holiday + workingday + weather + temp + humidity + windspeed, data = training)
modfit3_2 <- rpart(casual ~ year + month + hour + season + holiday + workingday + weather + temp + humidity + windspeed, data = training)


registered3 <- predict(modfit3_1, testing)
casual3 <- predict(modfit3_2, testing)
count3 <- registered3 + casual3
testing <- cbind(testing, registered3, casual3, count3)
s<-data.frame(datetime=testing$datetime,count=testing$count3)
write.csv(s,file="3-submit(Tree_complete_trainSet).csv",row.names=FALSE)
# File will be written and saved in working directory

# atemp is highly corelated to temp, no much variation between day,
Ntemp <-  data.Normalization (training$temp,type="n1",normalization="column")
Nhumidity <-  data.Normalization (training$humidity,type="n1",normalization="column")
Nwindspeed <-  data.Normalization (training$windspeed,type="n1",normalization="column")
training<-cbind(Ntemp, Nhumidity, Nwindspeed, training)


Ntemp <-  data.Normalization (testing$temp,type="n1",normalization="column")
Nhumidity <-  data.Normalization (testing$humidity,type="n1",normalization="column")
Nwindspeed <-  data.Normalization (testing$windspeed,type="n1",normalization="column")
testing<-cbind(Ntemp, Nhumidity, Nwindspeed, testing)
